Maps let you split documentation into reusable sections. 

You can nest one map inside another, and another inside that, as many levels as you need. This keeps even very large guides manageable.

Maps support inheritance — you can base a new map on an existing one so that changes in the base map update everywhere it is used.

You can also define variables for text that appears in many places — change the variable once and it updates everywhere.

When you publish a map the extension assembles all its components into a collection of markdown files we call a guide.

You can uninstall the extension at any time and the published markdown files still work with standard tools.

You can edit maps with the Map Editor or with the Json editor.

While building, you edit inside VS Code using the Map Editor or the JSON files directly. The extension provides intellisense for variables and checks all the plumbing is safe, including for circular references.

It also handles images and other files automatically so links work after publishing.


Routing lets one map call another map and then return to the original path.

This is useful when you want to keep the main guide simple. A complex section lives in its own map.

The called map can have one or more exit points. When the reader reaches an exit, they return to the next step in the calling map.

For example, imagine a troubleshooting map for a device. It can ask a question and then route to a more detailed diagnostic map. After the diagnostic map finishes, the reader returns to the main troubleshooting flow.


CONSIDER - add branches to expand on these (Also look at how the gifs in the extension pages work and use them but updated to this example):

1. **Variables for reusable text**  
   The demo and extension both emphasize variables heavily as a simple way to define text snippets (product names, common phrases, URLs, etc.) in one place. Changes update everywhere automatically.  
   This complements nesting and routing well — it's another tool that prevents duplication in large guides.

2. **Inheritance and changes propagating automatically**  
   Maps support inheritance/composition: you can base one map on another, and updates to the "parent" map flow through to all maps that use it. This is a key reason massive trees stay maintainable (single source of truth).

3. **On-the-fly assembly into clean Markdown**  
   When you publish or view the guide, the extension composes maps, expands variables, handles nesting/routing, and outputs standard Markdown (or HTML). No manual rebuilding of everything.

4. **Editor tools in VS Code**  
   You work with a visual Map Editor alongside the raw JSON view, plus IntelliSense for variables, validation (e.g., no circular references), and automatic handling of assets and relative links. This makes editing feel familiar to developers.

5. **No lock-in and full portability**  
   Everything ends up as ordinary Markdown files. You can uninstall the extension and continue working with the published files using any tools or static site generator.

6. **Assets and link handling**  
   The system automatically copies local images/files to the publish folder and adjusts links so nothing breaks.

